  "prompt": "What three books should an economics undergraduate read?",
  "response": "Here are three essential books for an economics undergraduate:\n\n1. \"Wealth of Nations\" by Adam Smith\n- Classic foundational text in economic theory\n- Explains market mechanisms, division of labor, and free market principles\n- Considered the cornerstone of modern economic thinking\n\n2. \"Capital\" by Thomas Piketty\n- Modern analysis of economic inequality\n- Provides deep insights into wealth distribution and economic dynamics\n- Offers a contemporary perspective on political economy\n\n3. \"Thinking, Fast and Slow\" by Daniel Kahneman\n- Explores behavioral economics and decision-making psychology\n- Explains cognitive biases and how they impact economic choices\n- Bridges psychology and economics in a highly accessible way\n\nThese books cover classical economic theory, contemporary economic analysis, and behavioral economics, providing a well-rounded perspective for an undergraduate student.",
